@article
    @title=Configuring 16-color console
    @key=hrd-console
    @ingroup=hrd
    @brief=How to configure the 16-color (standard console)

    The 16-color console configuration is used when XCE is started under the regular console window.

    To define the colors use [c]cfore[/c] and [c]cback[/c] attributes of the [c]assign[/c] keyword.
    The value of the attribute is the color index as specified below prefixed with a sharp sign (#).
    BOTH colors shall be specified.

    The console colors are shown below:

    [img=img/console_colors.png]
@end

@article
    @title=Configuring true-color console
    @key=hrd-tc
    @ingroup=hrd
    @brief=How to configure the true-color (console2-trc or conemu consoles)

    The true-color console configuration is used when XCE is started under the console2-trc or conemu simulators.

    [b]How to run XCE under ConEmu simulator[/b]

    1) Use 32-bit FAR and 32-bit ConEmu always, even on 64-bit system.

    2) In the settings check on "TrueMod (24 bit color) Support" option on the "Features/Color Settings" tab.

    3) In the setting check off "Long Console Output" settings on the "Startup/Output" tab.

    Then run FAR via ConEmu shortcut and run XCE from that instance for FAR. XCE will automatically detect ConEmu and will use
    true color settings from the color scheme.

    [b]How to configure colors under ConEmu simulator[/b]

    To define the colors use [c]fore[/c] and [c]back[/c] attributes of the [c]assign[/c] keyword. The value of the attributes is
    a hexadecimal RGB squad prefixed with a sharp sign (#). The colors are specified in the following order: bbggrr, each value in range between 00 and
    ff. BOTH colors shall be specified.

    You can also specify [c]style[/c]. The style is a number which corresponds to a style or their combination prefixed with a sharp sign (#).

    The following styles are supported by ConEmu:

    @table
        @row
            @col
                0
            @end
            @col
                No style specified, show the regular view of the text.
            @end
        @end
        @row
            @col
                1
            @end
            @col
                Bold
            @end
        @end
        @row
            @col
                2
            @end
            @col
                Italic
            @end
        @end
        @row
            @col
                4
            @end
            @col
                Underline.
            @end
        @end
    @end

    To specify a combination of styles just write the sum of the numbers, for example 5 is (4 + 1) means bold AND underline, and
    3 (2 + 1) means bold and italic.
@end
